canonical:
  title: 釣名諷
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 釣魚利其肉釣名何所利名乃實之賓有主賓自至無實享虛名適爲身所累龍伯釣六鼇此釣眞壯矣太公釣文王其釣本無餌釣名異於此僥倖一時耳有如無鹽女塗飾蹔容媚粉落露其眞見者嘔而避釣名作賢人何代無顔子釣名作循吏何邑非龔遂鄙哉公孫弘爲相乃布被小矣武昌守投錢飮井水淸畏人之知楊震眞君子吾作釣名篇以諷好名士
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 釣名諷
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 釣魚利其肉。釣名何所利。名乃實之賓。有主賓自至。無實享虛名。適爲身所累。龍伯釣六鼇。此釣眞壯矣。太公釣文王。其釣本無餌。釣名異於此。僥倖一時耳。有如無鹽女。塗飾蹔容媚。粉落露其眞。見者嘔而避。釣名作賢人。何代無顔子。釣名作循吏。何邑非龔遂。鄙哉公孫弘。爲相乃布被。小矣武昌守。投錢飮井水。淸畏人之知。楊震眞君子。吾作釣名篇。以諷好名士。
korean:
  title: 명성을 낚으려는데 대한 풍자
  author: 이규보
  language: kor
  text: |-
    고기 낚는 것은 고기 먹는 것 얻지마는
    이름은 낚아 무슨 이익되는가
    이름이란 곧 실상의 손이거니
    주인(실상) 있으면 손은 스스로 오네
    실상이 없이 헛이름만 누리면
    마침내 그 몸에 괴로움 되네
    용백은 여섯 마리 큰 자라 낚았나니
    그 낚기는 진실로 장한 것이네
    태공이 문왕을 낚을 때에는
    그 낚시에 원래 미끼 없었네
    그러나 이름 낚기는 이와 달라
    한때의 요행 뿐이네
    그것은 마치 추한 여자의 분 발라
    꾸며 잠깐 이쁜 것
    분이 지워지면 참 모양이 드러나
    보는 사람이 구역하고 피함과 같네
    이름을 낚아 어진 사람 된다면
    어느 대엔 안자 없으리
    이름을 낚아 착한 관원 된다면
    어느 고을인들 공수(한나라의 명수) 아니리
    야비하여라 저 공손홍은
    정승이 되어 베이블을 덮었거니
    작기도 하다 무창태수는
    돈을 주고서 우물 물을 마셨네
    청백하면서 사람 알까 두려워 했나니
    양진은 진실로 참 군자였네
    내 여기 조명편을 지어서 이름낚기
    좋아하는 선비를 풍자하노라
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0070_010_0220&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 안자(顔子) : '
    value: 공자(孔子)의 수제자(首弟子)이므로, 현인(賢人)의 대표로 들었다.
english:
  title: A Satire on Fishing for Fame
  author: Lee Gyeou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To fish for flesh brings meat to the table—
    but what profit comes from fishing for a name?

    A name is merely the shadow of substance;
    where substance dwells, shadow follows unbidden.
    But to feast on empty fame alone
    is to burden the body with suffering.

    Lung-po who hooked six great turtles—
    that was fishing of true magnificence!
    Tai-kung who hooked King Wen
    fished with no bait at all.

    But fishing for fame differs from this:
    it is mere chance, a fleeting gamble.

    Like a plain woman who paints her face,
    adorning herself with powder and rouge for a moment's beauty—
    when the powder falls away, truth is revealed,
    and all who see her turn in disgust.

    Fish for the name of a sage?
    In any age, there are Yans and Huis.
    Fish for the name of a virtuous magistrate?
    In any district, there are Gongs and Suiyis.

    How shameful was Gongsun Hong,
    who as Prime Minister wore rough cloth—
    yet how petty was the magistrate of Wuchang,
    who paid for water from the well!

    Yang Zhen—he alone was truly pure,
    fearing not that men might know his virtue.

    I write this satire on fishing for fame
    to mock those scholars enamored with names.
  footnotes:
    - Yan Hui was the foremost disciple of Confucius and represents the archetype of the wise sage. Here the poet uses his name to suggest that anyone seeking fame as a sage merely mimics the truly virtuous.
    - Gongsun Hong served as Prime Minister during the Han dynasty but maintained humble appearances; Gongsui (公遂) was a renowned virtuous magistrate of the same period. The poem uses these historical figures as contrasts to show the hollowness of merely performing virtue.
    - Yang Zhen was a famous Han official known for his integrity and refusal of bribes, embodying genuine moral character rather than mere reputation.
